hypersensitivity. It involves cell-mediated immunity where autoreactive T cells recognize and destroy insulin-producing beta cells in the pancreatic islets. This T cell-mediated destruction is characteristic of type IV hypersensitivity reactions, which are delayed-type responses mediated by T cells rather than antibodies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other types of hypersensitivity:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnaphylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E is a type I (immediate) hypersensitivity reaction mediated by IgE antibodies, resulting in mast cell degranulation and release of histamine and other inflammatory mediators.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic lupus erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily a type III hypersensitivity reaction involving immune complex deposition, though it has features of multiple hypersensitivity types.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune haemolytic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is a type II hypersensitivity reaction where antibodies target red blood cell antigens, leading to complement activation and cell destruction.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGoodpasture syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a type II hypersensitivity reaction characterized by antibodies against basement membrane components in the kidneys and lungs.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EType IV hypersensitivity reactions are distinguished by their delayed onset (typically 24-72 hours after exposure), lack of antibody involvement, and the central role of T cells in mediating tissue damage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type IV hypersensitivity reactions are cell-mediated immune responses involving T cells rather than antibodies.","Type 1 diabetes mellitus is characterized by T cell-mediated destruction of pancreatic beta cells.","Type IV hypersensitivity reactions typically develop over 24-72 hours after exposure to an antigen."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 6; pages 204-205."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79129"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20862"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79129"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-01T17:37:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T17:37:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13737"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96487"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11020"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Hypersensitivity reactions","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11595"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diseases of the immune system","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":5,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:55:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:55:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12682"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Type IV - T-cell mediated: D (Delayed Type - purified protei